      "abstract": "Medium- and long-chain triglycerides (MLCTs) integrate the metabolic advantages of medium-chain fatty acids and long-chain fatty acids, demonstrating significant potential in functional foods and infant nutrition. This review summarizes methods for chemically and enzymatically synthesizing MLCTs, highlighting that enzymatic synthesis has attracted more and more attention due to its mild reaction conditions and environmental friendliness. However, the process often involves adverse factors such as high viscosity and elevated temperatures, which compromise lipase activity, stability. To address these challenges, this article systematically examines strategies for enhancing lipase catalytic performance, including optimization of external factors, enzyme modification techniques, and computer-aided rational design. Notably, computer-aided rational design enables precise enhancement of enzymatic properties through hydration layer optimization, disulfide bond engineering, and substrate tunnel remodeling. These innovations address critical bottlenecks in MLCTs biosynthesis and establish a theoretical framework for developing next-generation lipases with industrial applicability.",
